T1  - Management Information Systems, Communications, and Departmental Power: An Integrative Model
AU  - Saunders, Carol Stoak
Y1  - 1981/07/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285782
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4285782
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 431
EP  - 442
VL  - 6
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - After a review of related theoretical and empirical research, I develop a theoretical framework that positively relates the use of management information systems to determinants of departmental power, including interdepartmental communications. The determinants of power are adapted from the theory of strategic contingencies [Hickson, Hinings, Lee, Schneck, & Pennings, 1971] and this theory is modified by the introduction of the importance of departmental tasks as a mediating variable in the relationship between power and its determinants.
AB  - After a review of related theoretical and empirical research, I develop a theoretical framework that positively relates the use of management information systems to determinants of departmental power, including interdepartmental communications. The determinants of power are adapted from the theory of strategic contingencies [Hickson, Hinings, Lee, Schneck, & Pennings, 1971] and this theory is modified by the introduction of the importance of departmental tasks as a mediating variable in the relationship between power and its determinants.
