TY  - JOUR
T1  - Exploring the Meaning of “Good” Management
AU  - Koprowski, Eugene J.
Y1  - 1981/07/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285788
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4285788
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 459
EP  - 467
VL  - 6
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Recently, good management has come to be equated in theory with practices that increase worker satisfaction. This may inadvertently be contributing to low productivity, narcissism, and groupthink among the work force. Exploring contributions from history, philosophy, and literature, I conclude that while definitions of good may be contextual, there is little evidence to support a ?contented cow? approach to management. Definitions that stress human growth and productivity may be of greater long-range benefit to our society.
AB  - Recently, good management has come to be equated in theory with practices that increase worker satisfaction. This may inadvertently be contributing to low productivity, narcissism, and groupthink among the work force. Exploring contributions from history, philosophy, and literature, I conclude that while definitions of good may be contextual, there is little evidence to support a ?contented cow? approach to management. Definitions that stress human growth and productivity may be of greater long-range benefit to our society.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285788
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1981.4285788
Y2  - 2026/04/24
