TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Integrated Management System: Lessons from the Japanese Experience, 
AU  - Hatvany, Nina
AU  - Pucik, Vladimir
Y1  - 1981/07/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285790
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1981.4285790
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 469
EP  - 480
VL  - 6
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Japanese management is characterized by a focus on the maximum utilization of human resources. This philosophy of management is realized through three general strategies: development of an internal labor market, articulation of a unique company philosophy, and intensive socialization of employees. These strategies in turn are manifested in a number of specific management techniques. These techniques can be adapted by businesses in other countries, and indeed some of them (e.g., long tenure, job rotation, consultative decision making) are in use in a number of top American companies.
AB  - Japanese management is characterized by a focus on the maximum utilization of human resources. This philosophy of management is realized through three general strategies: development of an internal labor market, articulation of a unique company philosophy, and intensive socialization of employees. These strategies in turn are manifested in a number of specific management techniques. These techniques can be adapted by businesses in other countries, and indeed some of them (e.g., long tenure, job rotation, consultative decision making) are in use in a number of top American companies.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1981.4285790
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1981.4285790
Y2  - 2026/04/24
